            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this property tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Property tax is usually charged by local governments on the
                value of land and buildings. The exact rules differ by country
                and municipality, but the core idea is the same: a tax rate is
                applied to a taxable value of the property.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>General formula</strong><br />
                \[ \text{Property tax} = (\text{Assessed value} -
                \text{Exemptions}) \times \text{Tax rate} - \text{Tax credits}
                \]
              </div>

              <p>This calculator lets you model three common systems:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Percentage of taxable value</strong> – common in the
                  US, UK council tax bands (effective rate), many EU
                  municipalities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mill rate</strong> – rate per 1,000 of assessed value
                  (e.g. 20 mills = 2%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fixed amount per unit</strong> – e.g. a fixed amount
                  per square metre, per room, or per tax band.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Step-by-step calculation</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Determine assessed value</strong><br />
                  Some jurisdictions tax the full market value; others use an
                  assessment ratio.
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Assessed value} = \begin{cases} \text{User-entered
                    assessed value}, & \text{if provided} \\ \text{Market value}
                    \times \text{Assessment ratio}, & \text{otherwise}
                    \end{cases} \]
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Subtract exemptions / reliefs</strong><br />
                  These reduce the taxable base (e.g. primary residence, senior,
                  disability, agricultural use).
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Taxable value} = \max(0,\ \text{Assessed value} -
                    \text{Exemptions}) \]
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply the tax rate</strong><br />
                  Depending on the system:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <em>Percentage:</em> \(\text{Rate} = \frac{\text{rate\%} +
                      \text{local rate\%}}{100}\)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Mill rate:</em> \(\text{Rate} = \frac{\text{mills} +
                      \text{local mills}}{1000}\)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <em>Per unit:</em> \(\text{Tax} = \text{Units} \times
                      \text{Rate per unit} + \text{Fixed charge}\)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Gross tax} = \begin{cases} \text{Taxable value}
                    \times \text{Rate}, & \text{percentage or mill} \\
                    \text{Units} \times \text{Rate per unit} + \text{Fixed
                    charge}, & \text{per unit} \end{cases} \]
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Subtract tax credits</strong><br />
                  Credits reduce the bill directly:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    \[ \text{Net tax} = \max(0,\ \text{Gross tax} - \text{Tax
                    credits}) \]
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example: percentage system</h3>
              <p>Suppose:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Market value: $350,000</li>
                <li>Assessment ratio: 80% → assessed value = $280,000</li>
                <li>Exemptions: $25,000 (primary residence)</li>
                <li>Tax rate: 1.0% + local 0.2% = 1.2%</li>
                <li>Tax credits: $300</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Taxable value = 280,000 − 25,000 = 255,000</li>
                <li>Gross tax = 255,000 × 1.2% = 3,060</li>
                <li>Net tax = 3,060 − 300 = 2,760</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The calculator will also show the effective tax rate:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{Effective rate} = \frac{\text{Net tax}}{\text{Market
                value}} \times 100\% \]
              </div>

              <h2>Key concepts: property tax terminology</h2>
              <h3>Market value vs. assessed value</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Market value</strong> – what the property would likely
                  sell for in an open market.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Assessed value</strong> – the value used by the tax
                  authority, often a percentage of market value or a cadastral
                  value.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Exemptions and reliefs</h3>
              <p>Common examples include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Primary residence / homestead exemption</li>
                <li>Senior citizen or disability exemptions</li>
                <li>Agricultural or historic property relief</li>
                <li>Low-income or means-tested reductions</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Mill rate vs. percentage rate</h3>
              <p>
                A <strong>mill</strong> is one-thousandth of the currency unit.
                A mill rate of 20 means 20 per 1,000 of assessed value.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{Rate as decimal} = \frac{\text{Mill rate}}{1000}
                \quad\Rightarrow\quad 20\ \text{mills} = 0.02 = 2\% \]
              </div>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>Is this calculator valid for my country?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator is designed to be
                <strong>jurisdiction-agnostic</strong>. It models the core math
                used in most property tax systems (assessed value, exemptions,
                rate, credits). However, each country and municipality has its
                own rules, bands, and reliefs. Always confirm with your local
                tax authority or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>

              <h3>How often is property tax paid?</h3>
              <p>
                Property tax is usually calculated on a yearly basis but may be
                collected monthly, quarterly, or in other instalments. Use the
                “Billing frequency” option to see how much you would pay per
                period.
              </p>

              <h3>Can property tax change over time?</h3>
              <p>Yes. Your bill can change if:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>The market or assessed value of your property changes.</li>
                <li>The local tax rate or mill rate is adjusted.</li>
                <li>
                  Your exemptions or reliefs change (for example, you move in
                  and qualify for a primary residence exemption).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Disclaimer</h3>
              <p>
                This tool is for
                <strong>educational and planning purposes only</strong>. It does
                not replace official calculations from your local tax authority,
                and it is not tax or legal advice. For binding figures, consult
                the relevant government office or a qualified professional.
              </p>
